First test of D4MUV9 in lysate

Copyright (C) 2018 Martin Engqvist Lab

Experiment

This test is identical to the LOX test done on array 2, except that this time we use E. coli lysate containing a recombinant lactate oxidase. This is the form in which we would be performing the enzyme assays in an application. We test BSA and Tween/Triton as well as different substrates, just like in the other test. The enzyme in question is D4MUV9.

Experimental data collected on 301018 (DDMMYY) in Petter Wolls group at Karolinska using a BioMark instrument.

# make all combinations of wells
mixed.df <- expand.grid(sample.df$sample_well, assay.df$assay_well)

# fix the colnames
colnames(mixed.df) <- c('sample_well', 'assay_well')

# add in the original data
mixed.df <- merge(mixed.df, sample.df, by='sample_well')
mixed.df <- merge(mixed.df, assay.df, by='assay_well')


# calculate final 
mixed.df$final_well <- paste(mixed.df$sample_well, mixed.df$assay_well, sep='-')

mixed.df$final_fluorescein_conc <- mixed.df$assay_fluorescein_conc/10 + mixed.df$sample_fluorescein_conc/1.1
mixed.df$final_fluorescein_unit <- mixed.df$assay_fluorescein_unit

mixed.df$final_amplex_red_conc <- mixed.df$assay_amplex_red_conc/10 
mixed.df$final_amplex_red_unit <- mixed.df$assay_amplex_red_unit

mixed.df$final_substrate_name <- mixed.df$assay_substrate_name
mixed.df$final_substrate_conc <- mixed.df$assay_substrate_conc/10 
mixed.df$final_substrate_unit <- mixed.df$assay_substrate_unit

mixed.df$final_bsa_conc <- mixed.df$assay_bsa_conc/10 
mixed.df$final_bsa_unit <- mixed.df$assay_bsa_unit

mixed.df$final_enzyme_name <- mixed.df$sample_enzyme_name
mixed.df$final_enzyme_conc <- mixed.df$sample_enzyme_conc/1.1 
mixed.df$final_enzyme_unit <- mixed.df$sample_enzyme_unit

Load data

So now we have the conditions in the final wells. Time to load up the measured data. From the data file that goes with this script (1_1530021086_array_4_raw.csv) I manually exported the ROX and FAM signal separately to tsv files. Load the data and then combine with my condition file.

# read the experimental data obtained from the BioMark
rox.df <- read.table(paste(INTERMEDIATE, 'flex_six_first_test', 'Array_4', '3_1530021086_array_4_rox.tsv', sep='/'), sep='\t', header=TRUE)
colnames(rox.df) <- c(c('final_well'), paste0('rox_cycle_', seq(length(colnames(rox.df))-1)))

fam.df <- read.table(paste(INTERMEDIATE, 'flex_six_first_test', 'Array_4', '4_1530021086_array_4_fam.tsv', sep='/'), sep='\t', header=TRUE)
colnames(fam.df) <- c(c('final_well'), paste0('fam_cycle_', seq(length(colnames(fam.df))-1)))


# Add the data into my frame with concentration info

A look at the raw data as a heatmap.

# ----- Define a function for plotting a matrix ----- #
# from http://www.phaget4.org/R/image_matrix.html
myImagePlot <- function(x, ...){
     min <- 0
     max <- 65000
     yLabels <- rownames(x)
     xLabels <- colnames(x)
     title <-c()
  # check for additional function arguments
  if( length(list(...)) ){
    Lst <- list(...)
    if( !is.null(Lst$zlim) ){
       min <- Lst$zlim[1]
       max <- Lst$zlim[2]
    }
    if( !is.null(Lst$yLabels) ){
       yLabels <- c(Lst$yLabels)
    }
    if( !is.null(Lst$xLabels) ){
       xLabels <- c(Lst$xLabels)
    }
    if( !is.null(Lst$title) ){
       title <- Lst$title
    }
  }
# check for null values
if( is.null(xLabels) ){
   xLabels <- c(1:ncol(x))
}
if( is.null(yLabels) ){
   yLabels <- c(1:nrow(x))
}

layout(matrix(data=c(1,2), nrow=1, ncol=2), widths=c(4,1), heights=c(1,1))

 # Red and green range from 0 to 1 while Blue ranges from 1 to 0
 ColorRamp <- colorRampPalette(c('#222222', '#EEEEEE'))(n = 256)
 ColorLevels <- seq(min, max, length=length(ColorRamp))

 # Reverse Y axis
 reverse <- nrow(x) : 1
 yLabels <- yLabels[reverse]
 x <- x[reverse,]

 # Data Map
 par(mar = c(3,5,2.5,2))
 image(1:length(xLabels), 1:length(yLabels), t(x), col=ColorRamp, xlab="",
 ylab="", axes=FALSE, zlim=c(min,max))
 if( !is.null(title) ){
    title(main=title)
 }
axis(BELOW<-1, at=1:length(xLabels), labels=xLabels, cex.axis=0.7)
 axis(LEFT <-2, at=1:length(yLabels), labels=yLabels, las= HORIZONTAL<-1,
 cex.axis=0.7)

 # Color Scale
 par(mar = c(3,2.5,2.5,2))
 image(1, ColorLevels,
      matrix(data=ColorLevels, ncol=length(ColorLevels),nrow=1),
      col=ColorRamp,
      xlab="",ylab="",
      xaxt="n")

 layout(1)
}
# ----- END plot function ----- #



make_heatmap <- function(mat_data){

  color_scale <- colorRampPalette(c('#1A1A1A', '#EEEEEE'))(n = 256)
  
  # adjust the color scale. Max value sems to be around 65,000
  max_val <- max(mat_data)
  if (max_val > 65000){
    color_end <- 256
  }else{
    color_end <- round((max_val/65000) * 256)
  }
  color_scale <- color_scale[1:color_end]
  
  image(mat_data, 
          axes=FALSE, 
          col = color_scale, 
          xlab='Assay', 
          ylab='Sample')
}

This looks good. Any bad loading should lead to half the signal. I dont seem to see that. So both tween/triton concentrations seem to work well to load E. coli lysate.

Next lets compare whether the sample tween/triton concentration had an effect on the enzyme activity.

ggplot(all.df, aes(x=final_enzyme_conc, y=rox_cycle_15, shape = factor(sample_tween_conc), color = factor(sample_tween_conc)))+
    geom_point() + 
    scale_color_manual(values = c('0.01' = 'darkorange2', '0.1' = 'darkgreen'), name='Tween and Triton conc.') + 
    scale_shape_manual(values = c('0.01' = 21, '0.1' = 25), name='Tween and Triton conc.') +
    ggtitle('D4MUV9 dilution series in different detergents, activity with three substrates') +
    xlab('Relative enzyme dilution') + 
    ylab('Signal in ROX channel (fluorescence)') +
    facet_grid(~final_substrate_name)

The detergent seems to have very little effect on the activity. If anything, the 0.1 concentration appears to give more variable data for the glycolate measurements. Oddly though there seems to be a falloff in activity at the lowest dilution 2x dilution (the 0.5 value). This is particularly visible for the lactate signal. So somwhat higher dilution rates appear to be optimal to detect activity. About 10x dilution or so.

ggplot(all.df, aes(x=final_enzyme_conc, y=rox_cycle_15, shape = factor(final_bsa_conc), color = factor(final_bsa_conc)))+

As previously seen with LOX, the BSA has little to no effect on the assays (compare orange and green). So peroxidase adsorption is not a problem it seems.

We did do kinetic measurements of the enzymes. Meeaning that we cycled 15 times at 20C for 1 minute. That gives us 15 measurements of fluorescence. Im interested in seeing whether we can actually see signal increase over time.
